{
  "slug": "the-smallest-useful-refactor",
  "title": "The smallest useful refactor",
  "category": "coding",
  "kicker": "Code health",
  "hook": "A refactor does not need a parade. Sometimes the best version is a tiny move that makes tomorrow obvious.",
  "readMinutes": 5,
  "date": "2026-06-22",
  "tags": [
    "refactoring",
    "maintainability"
  ],
  "beats": [
    {
      "num": "01 · the shape",
      "heading": "Big cleanup is where scope goes to hide",
      "blocks": [
        {
          "type": "prose",
          "html": "<p class=\"body\">The dangerous refactor starts with \"while I am here\" and ends with a pull request nobody can review. The safer move is to make the next change easy, then stop.</p>"
        },
        {
          "type": "terminal",
          "title": "git · tiny diff",
          "caption": "The useful signal is usually already there.",
          "lines": [
            {
              "t": "$ git diff --stat",
              "c": "pr"
            },
            {
              "t": "billing.ts        | 12 ++++++------",
              "c": ""
            },
            {
              "t": "billing.test.ts   | 18 ++++++++++++++++++",
              "c": ""
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "graph",
          "center": "change",
          "nodes": [
            "tests",
            "API",
            "data",
            "logs",
            "review",
            "deploy"
          ],
          "caption": "A tiny patch rarely touches only one thing. Push it and watch the review surface appear.",
          "action": "ship the diff",
          "idle": "change looks calm",
          "running": "checking blast radius...",
          "done": "6 engineering checks touched"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "num": "02 · the move",
      "heading": "Refactor around the change",
      "blocks": [
        {
          "type": "prose",
          "html": "<p class=\"body\">Extract the branch you need to touch, name the concept, add a test around current behavior, then make the actual feature change in a separate commit if possible.</p>"
        },
        {
          "type": "code",
          "file": "billing.ts",
          "code": "function isRetryablePaymentError(error) {\n  return [\"timeout\", \"rate_limited\"].includes(error.code);\n}\n\nif (isRetryablePaymentError(error)) retryLater();",
          "caption": "A small name can remove a lot of local guessing."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "num": "03 · the check",
      "heading": "Make review easy",
      "blocks": [
        {
          "type": "prose",
          "html": "<p class=\"body\">A useful refactor should have boring tests and a boring diff. If the reviewer cannot tell behavior stayed the same, split the patch.</p>"
        },
        {
          "type": "lab",
          "title": "change confidence lab",
          "caption": "Flip the switches and watch the story turn into a tiny operating model.",
          "toggles": [
            {
              "label": "contract test",
              "off": "shape can drift silently",
              "on": "public behavior pinned",
              "weight": 28
            },
            {
              "label": "rollback note",
              "off": "recovery is folklore",
              "on": "exit ramp written down",
              "weight": 22
            },
            {
              "label": "logs with ids",
              "off": "debugging by vibes",
              "on": "request can be traced",
              "weight": 24
            },
            {
              "label": "small diff",
              "off": "reviewer has to excavate",
              "on": "review path is narrow",
              "weight": 26
            }
          ],
          "minLabel": "guessy",
          "maxLabel": "safe",
          "low": "fragile: this change still depends on hope and a lucky deploy",
          "mid": "better: the main risk has at least one alarm around it",
          "high": "solid: tests, observability, and review all agree on the shape"
        },
        {
          "type": "stats",
